p, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Bescot, Staffordshire, England":"Bescot, Staffordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Sutton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places called Sutton, named with Old English <i>sūth</i> ‘south, southern’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The English surname is also common in Ireland (Wexford, Kildare), where it has been established since the 13th century and Gaelicized as <b>de Sutún</b>.","Jewish (from the former Ottoman Empire, including Syria): unexplained.","English: topographic name from Middle English <i>(bi) suthentune</i> ‘(at the place to the) south of the village’."],"variants":[{"name":"Setton","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Avi, Ronit, Yossef.  French Andree, Henri, Jacques, Maryse.","Jewish (from the Ottoman Empire): altered form of   Sutton  .","English (Middlesex): variant of   Seaton  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":5,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":18,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705195,"age":72,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Sutton was born about 1310, in Shropshire, England, her father, John Sutton I, was 26 and her mother, Margaret Somery, was 21. She had at least 1 daughter with Sir Roger Hillary."},"et":{"about 1310–":"umbes 1310–Surnud","1305–1354":"1305–1354","1306–1356":"1306–1356","1308–1359":"1308–1359","1310–Female":"1310–Surnud","1305–1357":"1305–1357","1328–1403":"1328–1403","1325–1350":"1325–1350","1286–1338":"1286–1338","1290–1384":"1290–1384","1286":"1286","1384":"1384","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1290":"1290","1338":"1338","1305":"1305","1315":"1315","1403":"1403","1359":"1359","1325":"1325","1302":"1302","1357":"1357","1356":"1356","about 1325":"umbes 1325","1310":"1310","1354":"1354","about 1310":"umbes 1310","1308":"1308","1317":"1317","1328":"1328","1306":"1306","Warsop, Nottinghamshire, England":"Warsop, Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Bescot, Staffordshire, England":"Bescot, Staffordshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1310–":"noin 1310–Kuollut","1305–1354":"1305–1354","1306–1356":"1306–1356","1308–1359":"1308–1359","1310–Female":"1310–Kuollut","1305–1357":"1305–1357","1328–1403":"1328–1403","1325–1350":"1325–1350","1286–1338":"1286–1338","1290–1384":"1290–1384","1286":"1286","1384":"1384","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1290":"1290","1338":"1338","1305":"1305","1315":"1315","1403":"1403","1359":"1359","1325":"1325","1